When, to refresh his mind, he went out from home into the marketplace and saw all the artisans hard at work in their shops, often on his return he would at once resume his work as if warned by some grave censor saying, "We too must exert ourselves in the task we have undertaken."

In the Spring when he saw the fields and the hills in bloom and noticed all the plants and trees bearing the greatest promise of fruit to come, deep sadness overcame him, and he would reproach himselve in these words, "Now you too, Battista, must bring forth some fruit from your studies."

And in the Autumn when he saw the fields heavy with the harvest and the trees laden with fruit, he was so afflicted with sadness that he was even seen on occasion to weep from sorrow and heard to murmur, "See, Leo, how on all sides witnesses and accusers of our idleness surround us! For what is there anywhere in nature which in the course of a whole year does not produce something of great advantage to men? But you, what do you have that you can bring forth by virtue of your profession, for the public good?"

Self-Portrait of a Universal Man

I'm a very low maintenance friend. I don't demand a lot from the people I'm friends with. I am perfectly content knowing I wont see anyone from Drew  this summer. And that doesn't mean I don't value their friendships, its just how I am. I know that even if I didn't talk to Seth or Ginny for the entire summer and the entire time they're in London, the day they came to Drew, things would be fine between us as if nothing happened. Hell, Ginny and I have already said that we're both fine if we don't see each other this summer. It'll still be cool. 

But who cares? No big deal. You want more. I plan on going back to Drew after not seeing any signs of Drewids, and only talking rarely, and think everything will be fine. For me, if someone weren't to talk to me an entire summer or visit me for an entire summer, and then I saw them on August 22nd, I'd be fine with it and there would be no ill feelings from me towards them. i guess I just expect people to feel the same, but I learned that some people don't. 

But it goes the same way from people from home, I'm fine not seeing you when I'm at school. Don't take that personally, its nothing against you. I don't undervalue our friendship, for me, i'm fine with not seeing you. For me it'll be fine, and I'd like for you guys to be fine with that, knowing full well that Its nothing personal, and that my feelings for you guys aren't lessened at all. 

I understand people have different definitions of friendships, but I respect yours, so respect mine. If your definition of being friends with someone is being a part of their life all the time even when you're not around, I respect that, but for me, I'm fine with not.

So there were two older guys across from me on a train...and I asked them the same question I ask everyone whenever conversation goes stale (a trick I stole from Lisa Apple.) 

"What was the best thing that happened to you today?"

The first man responded by telling me about his business and how he sealed the deal, broke the bank, delegated down, and all sorts of cliched business phrases. 

The other told me how he saw his grandaughter for the first time in a long time and about the life in her eyes and how there was nowhere else he'd rather be and how much she's grown and how he looks just like her mother, and how he'd give his life to make hers better and how they'll be together forever. 

I started to think about the path I've yet to take:
Be proud of brokering a deal or spending time with a child with the world in her eyes.

So what IS the measure of success? A happy family or a booming business?

I'm on this crossroads of the stereotypical twentysomething existentialism of "why?" I'm only 20 and want this fifth-life crisis to happen already where I just disappear to a deserted island somewhere and just live like Tom Hanks in Cast-Away.

I'm looking forward to retirement and I haven't even started working! 

I wanna care more about the answer to 26 across then the answer to Multiple Choice #26. 
I wanna worry about who fed the cat rather than who sent a fax. 
I wanna think about the weather instead of thinking about my taxes.

I could go on, but sorry, I'm not that witty.

I learned the power and bond of friendship from the classy broads (glickman, charlatte, erica, shaina, cathieeee, rob w. etc.) i learned how to love and felt the utter joy of someone looking happy when they see you from my shelly baby. i learned how to mature, how to document, how to be artistic, learned how to cooperate in a team from the entire ResLife crew, learned how to respect and appreciate myself from Drew Chen. unfortunately i recently learned that i have to leave. but most of all I learned that I learned more than I ever have about myself and life i in just one and a half years at Drew and no amount of classes or GPA or grades can take that away from me.

But the others would beat her anyway and Adupa cried, not because of the pain in her body, but because of the pain she felt at that great, vast empty wasteland where love should have been.
    That was what killed her. She demanded that her parents love her. She kept going back to their compound, almost next to Atum's and the closest to my own. Finally they took her in, and Adupa was happy and stopped crying. She stopped crying forever, because her parents went away and closed up the house's opening tight behind them, so tight that weak little Adupa could never have moved it if she had tried. But I doubt that she even thought of trying. She waited for them to come back with the food they promised her. When they came back she was still waiting for them. It was ten days later and her body was already almost too far gone to bury. In an Ik village who would notice the smell? And if she had cried, who would have noticed that? Her parents took what was left of her and threw it out--as one does the garbage--a good distance away. They even pulled some stones over it to stop the vultures and hyenas from scattering bits and pieces of their daughter in Atum's field; that would have been offensive for they were good neighbors and shared the same compound.

Imagine this:

You're on an airplane, sleeping with your head against the window, your heart set on being home this time three hours from now. All of a sudden, something goes very wrong. The plane stops moving across the air and instead starts falling through it. The lights are flickering and the movie is skipping. The plane dips hundreds of feet in seconds, and the yellow cups fall from the ceiling. They're a brighter shade of yellow than you remember, because unlike the demonstration, these cups have never been handled before. "Flight attendants take your seats now", you hear, the pilot's voice trembling over a cacophony of alert tones. You get that smell in the bridge of your nose like you've just been hit with a football. That's what the fear smells like. The plane is going down.

Four more drastic drops in under a minute. People are crying. For all the folklore about how your life flashes before your eyes, you're remarkably fixed on one vision - your parents. They're sleeping at this very moment, in a bedroom so quiet they can hear the clock in the kitchen. And you can see them, clear as can be. You wish you could see a playground or a first kiss, but all you can see is your parents sleeping. Huh. Well, that's that.

Several long minutes go by. Then, all at once, the lights come back on and the plane somehow rights itself. Some people cheer, but most people cry harder. The plane lands about an hour later, and as soon as you feel that touch down - hell, even when you were within 50 feet of the ground and could still technically survive a fall - you realize that however you brokered the deal between you and God worked; you've just been granted life in overtime.

Here's the question: what do you change? Whom do you call that you haven't spoken to in years? Whom do you realize has been toxic to your heart and drop with surprising ease? What trips do you cancel, and what trips do you book? What can't you be bothered with anymore? What's the new you like?


Think about that, and then ask one more question. Why not just change it all right now?
Tonight, for something so simple, was amazing.

I haven't felt good in a while. I've felt content. I'm working hard, but so what? I'm working too hard. I've got loads of homework that won't get done. And because its stuff from the past that i haven't kept up on, it'll pile up and the load will look quite impossible to knock down. So I don't do it. Acorn stuff, I can do that, for some reason thats the one thing I can do. RA stuff, its a lot more work than you'd think. I guess I just have to learn time management. Force myself to do things. Open up my planner to a random day and say "I'm gonna live to see this day..." and know that all the homework and shit isn't as important as that. 

I saw a commercial the other day about retirement or something. And I realized, here I am worrying about this petty shit...but I haven't even reached any point of my future yet. That all this stuff I'm avoiding doing is to build that future. That kind of motivated me...'get off your ass cuz your life hasn't even started yet...this is where you build your life so one day YOU can retire." 

Other times, (like after watching the movie Cast Away) I really wish I was on some deserted island alone somewhere. Less stress from these outside forces, everything you have to worry about is life or death, so you HAVE to do it. Not like..a journalism article that you haven't started yet...or a German test you hvaen't begun studying for that are BOTH for tomorrow. No, you just gotta get a coconut, kill a fish, knock out your tooth with an ice-skate. Maybe if I viewed everything as life or death I'd do it? Probably not.
